---
// Science-Backed Credibility Section
// Research-based methodology, no BS
---

<section
  class="py-16 md:py-24 px-4"
  style="background: linear-gradient(180deg, var(--color-dark) 0%, var(--color-rich-earth) 100%);"
>
  <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto">
    <h2
      class="text-3xl md:text-4xl lg:text-5xl font-extrabold mb-12 text-center leading-tight"
      style="color: var(--color-alabaster);"
    >
      Built on Research, Not Motivational Bullshit
    </h2>

    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-10 mb-12">
      <!-- Research Block 1 -->
      <div
        class="p-10 lg:p-12 rounded-2xl border-t-2 border border-[rgba(241,237,233,0.08)] hover:border-[rgba(0,208,156,0.2)] transition-all duration-300 hover:scale-[1.02] hover:shadow-[0_0_40px_rgba(0,208,156,0.15)]"
        style="background: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.6); backdrop-filter: blur(24px); border-top-color: var(--color-jade);"
      >
        <span
          class="inline-block text-xs font-bold px-3 py-1 rounded-lg mb-4"
          style="color: var(--color-jade); background: rgba(0, 208, 156, 0.1);"
          >01</span
        >
        <h3
          class="text-3xl font-bold mb-4 leading-snug"
          style="color: var(--color-alabaster);"
        >
          66 Days to Automaticity
        </h3>
        <p
          class="text-base leading-relaxed"
          style="color: var(--color-alabaster);"
        >
          Phillippa Lally's UCL study proves it: 66 days is the average
          timeframe for habit formation. Not 21 days. Not "whenever you feel
          like it." 66 days of showing up builds automatic behavior. That's the
          program length. That's the commitment.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Research Block 2 -->
      <div
        class="p-10 lg:p-12 rounded-2xl border-t-2 border border-[rgba(241,237,233,0.08)] hover:border-[rgba(0,208,156,0.2)] transition-all duration-300 hover:scale-[1.02] hover:shadow-[0_0_40px_rgba(0,208,156,0.15)]"
        style="background: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.6); backdrop-filter: blur(24px); border-top-color: var(--color-jade);"
      >
        <span
          class="inline-block text-xs font-bold px-3 py-1 rounded-lg mb-4"
          style="color: var(--color-jade); background: rgba(0, 208, 156, 0.1);"
          >02</span
        >
        <h3
          class="text-3xl font-bold mb-4 leading-snug"
          style="color: var(--color-alabaster);"
        >
          Identity-Based Change
        </h3>
        <p
          class="text-base leading-relaxed"
          style="color: var(--color-alabaster);"
        >
          We don't just track what you do. We change who you are. Based on James
          Clear's Atomic Habits framework, your actions shape your identity.
          Complete the program, become the person who doesn't need the program.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Research Block 3 -->
      <div
        class="p-10 lg:p-12 rounded-2xl border-t-2 border border-[rgba(241,237,233,0.08)] hover:border-[rgba(0,208,156,0.2)] transition-all duration-300 hover:scale-[1.02] hover:shadow-[0_0_40px_rgba(0,208,156,0.15)]"
        style="background: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.6); backdrop-filter: blur(24px); border-top-color: var(--color-jade);"
      >
        <span
          class="inline-block text-xs font-bold px-3 py-1 rounded-lg mb-4"
          style="color: var(--color-jade); background: rgba(0, 208, 156, 0.1);"
          >03</span
        >
        <h3
          class="text-3xl font-bold mb-4 leading-snug"
          style="color: var(--color-alabaster);"
        >
          Habit Stacking That Works
        </h3>
        <p
          class="text-base leading-relaxed"
          style="color: var(--color-alabaster);"
        >
          BJ Fogg's Tiny Habits research integrated into every program. Stack
          new behaviors on existing ones. Start small, build momentum, scale up.
          Science-backed progression, not random challenges.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p
      class="text-sm text-center italic max-w-2xl mx-auto"
      style="color: var(--color-faded-khaki);"
    >
      Methodology backed by peer-reviewed research in behavioral psychology. Not
      invented by some guru on Instagram.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>
